To connect your app.py with style.css, you only need ONE simple step in app.py:


---

âœ… STEP 1 â€” Load your CSS file inside app.py

At the TOP of your app.py (after imports), add this:

# Load external CSS
def load_css(file_name):
    with open(file_name, "r") as f:
        st.markdown(f"<style>{f.read()}</style>", unsafe_allow_html=True)

load_css("static/style.css")

âœ” This tells Streamlit to read your stylesheet
âœ” And apply it to the whole UI
âœ” Now your .chat-message, .user-msg, .bot-msg, .title, etc. will work


---

ðŸ“Œ Folder Structure (VERY IMPORTANT)

Your project should look like this:

project/
â”‚ app.py
â”‚ chat_history.db
â”‚ models/
â”‚ utils/
â”‚ data/
â”‚
â””â”€â”€ static/
       â”œâ”€â”€ style.css
       â”œâ”€â”€ user.png
       â””â”€â”€ bot.jfif

âœ” static/style.css
âœ” static/user.png
âœ” static/bot.jfif


---

ðŸ“Œ STEP 2 â€” Use CSS classes in app.py

Where you display chat, use this:

st.markdown(
    f"""
    <div class='chat-message user-msg'>
        <img src='static/user.png' width='25' style='vertical-align:middle;margin-right:6px;'>
        <strong>You:</strong> {message}
    </div>
    """,
    unsafe_allow_html=True
)

and for bot:

st.markdown(
    f"""
    <div class='chat-message bot-msg'>
        <img src='static/bot.jfif' width='25' style='vertical-align:middle;margin-right:6px;'>
        <strong>Bot:</strong> {message}
    </div>
    """,
    unsafe_allow_html=True
)


